<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALK LIKE A MAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What Susan Littwin says about men and women and how they occupy space is true 
("Walk Like a Man," Feb. 5). If men and women are going to continue to enter 
into and co-exist peacefully in each other's domains, then they must be 
respectful of the effect they create on one another. 
</P>
<P>
CLARE KIRKCONNELL 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040289-0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 38554 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 2, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Magazine; Page 6; Magazine Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
88 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALK LIKE A MAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unfortunately for us all, women still do struggle to fit into a man's world. 
But Littwin's use of an aerobics class to condemn this struggle further 
exemplifies a self-defeating attitude. Is it that women do aerobics and men 
make decisions in the board room? By her attacking her male counterpart in an 
aerobics class (on her turf, so to speak) at best defies the basic concept of a 
symmetry between men and women and at worst exemplifies a further separation of 
the sexes, and by a woman, yet. 
</P>
<P>
THOMAS CAMACHO 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
