<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISCOUNTER SERVICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the owner of a successful Help-U-Sell real estate office, I read with great 
interest David W. Myer's (March 12) discount brokers article as well as the 
response from several brokers in your "Letters" column (March 26). 
</P>
<P>
The response of these brokers typifies the lack of research and naivete of some 
so-called "full-service" competitors. 
</P>
<P>
We are licensed brokers and members of the local Board of Realtors. We submit 
(when it is in our seller's best interest) many of our listings to the Multiple 
Listing Service, put our phone number on the yard sign and in newspaper 
advertisements, screen the buyers, draw the real estate contract, cover all of 
the legal requirements and usher the transaction through escrow just as does 
the "full-service" brokerage. We are, in fact, a full-service brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
Why don't we charge a 6% commission? Because we don't hire hundreds of 
inexperienced licensees to knock on doors, cold call on the telephone, hand out 
little trinkets and spend 80% of our time just looking for clients. And we do 
not sell a "full-service package" unless the property and situation warrant it. 
</P>
<P>
TIMOTHY E. McCAULEY 
</P>
<P>
Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
