<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: FLUTIE MAY BATTLE KRAMER AT CALGARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Erik Kramer could face a short but significant hurdle in his hopes to succeed 
in professional football. 
</P>
<P>
After being cut by the Atlanta Falcons and New Orleans Saints of the National 
Football League, the former Burroughs High and Pierce College quarterback 
started the final four games of 1988 for the Calgary Stampeders of the Canadian 
Football League. 
</P>
<P>
This week, while Kramer was in Calgary for meetings with coaches, it was 
revealed that the Stampeders have begun negotiations to sign 1984 Heisman 
Trophy winner Doug Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
Officials of the financially strapped team concede that their chances of 
signing the 5-foot-9 Flutie are not good. Regardless, Kramer isn't fazed by the 
possibility that Flutie could be heading north. 
</P>
<P>
"The fact that pro teams are constantly looking at other quarterbacks isn't 
something that has just dawned on me," Kramer told the Calgary Herald. 
</P>
<P>
Nancy Nicholls, a two-time All-City selection from Cleveland High, has signed a 
letter of intent to play volleyball at Cal State Northridge. Nicholls is a 
middle blocker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
